%N A390915 Number of elements of the ring of n-adic integers that satisfy y^k = y for at least one integer k > 1.
%C A390915 Let Z_n denote the ring of n-adic integers.
%C A390915 By the n-adic Chinese Remainder Theorem (CRT), Z_n is isomorphic to a direct product of Z_p over the distinct prime divisors p of n.
%C A390915 Therefore, a(n) depends only on rad(n); in particular, a(n) is multiplicative.
%C A390915 For every odd prime p and every m >= 1, one has a(p^m) = a(p) = p. Indeed, in Z_p the equation y^k = y has exactly p solutions for suitable k > 1, namely y = 0 together with the p - 1 Teichmüller units, and the same solutions persist in Z_{p^m}.
%C A390915 Hence, exactly p - 1 units satisfy y^k = y for suitable integers k > 1, and together with y = 0, this yields a(p^m) = p.
%C A390915 Let n have exactly omega(n) distinct prime factors (p_1, p_2, ..., p_{omega(n)}) so that rad(n) := p_1*p_2*...*p_{omega(n)}.
%C A390915 In general, there exists a minimal integer t := t(n) (necessarily odd and greater than 2) such that y^t = y admits all the solutions of every equation of the form y^k = y in Z_n (for all integers k > 1). In particular, t = 3 if rad(n) = 2, and otherwise t = 1 + lcm(p_j - 1 : 1 <= j <= omega(n), p_j <> 2).
%C A390915 It follows that the equation y^t(n) = y has exactly a(n) solutions in the commutative ring of n-adic integers Z_n.
%D A390915 Kenneth Ireland and Michael Rosen, A Classical introduction to Modern Number Theory (2nd edition), Springer, New York, 1990.
%D A390915 Ivan Niven, Herbert S. Zuckerman, and Hugh L. Montgomery, An Introduction to the Theory of Numbers (5th edition), Wiley, New York, 1991.
%H A390915 James C. McMahon, <a href="/A390915/b390915.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..10000</a>
%H A390915 Gérard P. Michon, <a href="http://www.numericana.com/answer/p-adic.htm#integers">Introduction to p-adic integers</a>, Numericana.
%H A390915 Marco Ripà, <a href="https://zenodo.org/records/18023892">Solving the Fundamental Equation y^(tau(r)) = y in Z_r</a>, Zenodo, 2025.
%F A390915 For n odd, a(n) = product of the distinct primes dividing n;
%F A390915 for n even, a(n) = 3*(product of the odd primes dividing n).
%F A390915 a(n) = A007947(n) if n is odd, and a(n) = 3*A204455(n) otherwise.
%F A390915 From _Amiram Eldar_, Jan 13 2026: (Start)
%F A390915 Multiplicative with a(2^e) = 3 and a(p^e) = p for an odd prime p.
%F A390915 Sum_{k=2..n} a(k) ~ c * n^2, where c = (3/5)*A065463 = 0.4226653205... . (End)
%e A390915 a(2) = 3 since y^3 = y has exactly the 2-adic solutions 0, 1 and -1.
%t A390915 a[n_]:=If[OddQ[n],Last[Select[Divisors[n], SquareFreeQ]],3*Last[Select[Divisors[n], SquareFreeQ]]/2];Array[a,80,2] (* _James C. McMahon_, Dec 04 2025 *)
%t A390915 f[p_, e_] := p; f[2, e_] := 3; a[n_] := Times @@ f @@@ FactorInteger[n]; Array[a, 100, 2] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Jan 13 2026 *)
%o A390915 (Python)
%o A390915 def a(n):
%o A390915     m=n; r=1
%o A390915     if n%2==0:
%o A390915         r=3
%o A390915         while m%2==0: m//=2
%o A390915     p=3
%o A390915     while p*p<=m:
%o A390915         if m%p==0:
%o A390915             r*=p
%o A390915             while m%p==0: m//=p
%o A390915         p+=2
%o A390915     if m>1: r*=m
%o A390915     return r
